{
  "text_segment": "What it was, whether man or beast, I could not tell; I did not wait to catch another glance, but flew down the steep steps to the pier and along by the fish-market to the bridge, which was the only way to reach the East Cliff. The town was deserted, and I was glad of it, for I wanted no witness of Lucy's strange plight. The steps up the cliff are so many and so steep that it was a hard task to run up them, and my heart was beating with emotion and exertion. I think I must have been almost at the top when I saw the seat and the white figure, for I was then close enough to distinguish it, and to see that there was something long and dark bending over it. I called out, 'Lucy! Lucy!' and in a moment of dreadful suspense, the figure raised its head. I could see its face, which was pale, and its eyes, which seemed to be red. For a moment, as I came along the edge of the churchyard, the corner of the great church hid the seat from my view. When I could see it again, the moonlight was shining full upon it, and Lucy was there alone, with her head lying back on the arm of the seat. I ran to her and found her fast asleep, breathing in long, heavy gasps. As I came close, she, in her sleep, moved her hand to her throat and moaned. I was so anxious that I was clumsy, and when I went to wrap my shawl around her, I must have pinched or pricked her with the safety-pin, for she moved uneasily. I put my own shoes on her feet and then began to wake her. She woke with a start and a little cry, but she was her own sweet self, and with a gentle grace, she clung to me and let me lead her home. We met but one man, from whom we hid, and he seemed to be drunk. I was so worried about her that I took her to her own room and helped her to bed. Then she begged me not to say a word to any one, not even her mother, about her sleep-walking. I hesitated, but she was so earnest, and I did not want to frighten her mother, so I promised. When she was asleep, I locked the door and tied the key to my wrist, so that I should not be taken by surprise again."
}
